file=Executive Office/echo/marketplace/investor-update-generator/references/what_makes_good_updates.md · wmg:What Makes Good Investor Updates=Investors read dozens of monthly updates a month. The ones that produce help, raise reputation, and keep the cap table aligned share patterns; the ones that don't share a different set.\n\n · ### Highlights AND lowlights=- 3-5 wins specific enough to be falsifiable ("closed Acme at $80k ARR" — not "great enterprise momentum")\n- 2-4 lowlights — what missed, what's at risk, what's slow\n- Ratio: roughly 2:1 highlights:lowlights. All-positive is a red flag.\n · ### Hard numbers=- MRR / ARR (or revenue, or whatever your topline is)\n- Growth rate (MoM or QoQ)\n- Cash / runway in months\n- One key product metric (DAU, weekly active, or activation rate)\n- Hiring number (open / hired / lost)\n · ### Context, not just numbers=- Why did the metric move?\n- What's the next milestone you're targeting?\n- What's the bet you're making?\n · ### Specific asks=- Bad: "let us know if you can help"\n- Good: "Intros to (a) VPs of Engineering at SaaS companies 100-1000 employees in NA who're hiring senior backend, (b) finance leaders we should learn from on planning, (c) anyone with regulatory experience in [your sector]"\n\nThe specificity test: could the investor act on this without further clarification?\n · ### Forward-looking=- What's in next month?\n- What gates the next 3 months?\n- What decisions are coming up?\n\n · ### All-positive momentum=Updates that never have a lowlight tell investors that either (a) you're not paying attention to risks, or (b) you're managing them away from the update. Both are bad.\n · ### Vague metrics="Strong growth" without a number, "promising pipeline" without dollars. Investors discount what they can't quantify.\n · ### Generic asks="Let us know how you can help" produces no help. Specificity unlocks value.\n · ### Inconsistent reporting=Defining MRR one way in March and another way in April erodes trust. Pick definitions; stick to them.\n · ### Long format=2000+ word updates are skim-rate-dropping. Most investors are 5-10 minutes per read; format for that budget.\n · ### No cadence=Quarterly updates from a Series A company are too sparse. Skipping months without explanation produces silence anxiety.\n\n · c:Cadence=- **Pre-seed / Seed:** monthly is standard. Some weekly during a sprint.\n- **Series A:** monthly for first 2 years; can move to bi-monthly once stable.\n- **Later stage:** quarterly fine; supplement with significant-event updates.\n\n · d:Distribution=**Investors only:** safer for sensitive data; minimum surface area.\n**Investors + advisors:** often appropriate; advisors can act on asks.\n**Extended network (helpful operators):** broader help potential; risk of leakage.\n\nPick a list size you can sustain. 50 names is plenty for a Series A.\n\n · f:Format=**Email > Word doc > PDF**\n- Email is read; PDFs are downloaded and forgotten.\n- Use Bcc for distribution if you don't want recipients seeing each other.\n- Some founders use Foundersuite, Airbase, Visible.vc, etc. — fine if it gets sent; counterproductive if the tool becomes a barrier to writing.\n\n**Length:** target 600-800 words; 1000 if a particularly eventful month.\n\n · si:Sensitive Information=Some founders share more, some less:\n- **Always share:** topline metrics, runway, key risks, asks\n- **Often share:** detailed pipeline, competitive moves, churn analysis\n- **Sometimes share:** exact ARR (some prefer % growth instead), specific customer names\n- **Rarely share:** salary specifics, legal-sensitive context, trade secrets\n\nThe bar: would you be comfortable if this leaked? If not, leave it out or share verbally.\n\n · rfb:Recovery from Bad News=When the bad news is significant (large customer loss, key departure, missed targets, security incident):\n\n1. Send the update **early** — same day or next day, not in the next monthly\n2. Lead with the news — don't bury\n3. Be specific about: what happened, impact, response, next steps\n4. Be honest about what you don't yet know\n5. Schedule individual calls with major investors if severity warrants\n\nThe biggest mistake: investors learn about the bad thing from someone else first.\n\n · cm:Common Mistakes=1. **Skipping months.** Once the cadence breaks, it's hard to restart.\n2. **Update as PR.** Updates aren't pitches. The audience is already in.\n3. **Burying the lede.** Whatever's most important — say it first.\n4. **No metrics in writing.** Verbal updates don't substitute for written.\n5. **Wall of text.** Use sections, bullets, bold for scan-ability.\n6. **Different definitions monthly.** "MRR includes / excludes annual contracts" needs to stay constant.\n7. **Asks at the end.** Asks should be early enough that they survive skim-reads.\n\n · qs:Quick Self-Test=Before sending, ask:\n\n- [ ] Could a non-customer recognize the wins as wins (not vague claims)?\n- [ ] Did I include at least 2 lowlights / risks?\n- [ ] Are runway and topline visible in the first screen?\n- [ ] Are my asks specific enough that an investor could act on them today?\n- [ ] Is the update under 1000 words?\n- [ ] Did I send it within 5 business days of month-end?\n\nIf yes to all, send. If not, fix and re-check.\n